    {
      "content": "Queries",
      "pos": [
        11981,
        11988
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once you have defined your external data source and your external tables, you can use familiar SQL Database connection strings to connect to the database that has the Elastic Database query feature enabled.",
      "pos": [
        11989,
        12195
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can now use execute full read-only queries over your external tables—with some limitations explained in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>limitations section<ept id=\"p1\">](#preview-limitations)</ept> below.",
      "pos": [
        12196,
        12358
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Example<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: The following query performs a three-way join between warehouses, orders and order lines and uses several aggregates and a selective filter.",
      "pos": [
        12360,
        12513
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Assuming warehouses, orders and order lines are partitioned by the warehouse id column, an elastic database query can collocate the joins on the remote databases and can scale-out the processing of the expensive part of the query.",
      "pos": [
        12514,
        12744
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Stored procedure SP_ EXECUTE_FANOUT",
      "pos": [
        13158,
        13193
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "SP\\_EXECUTE\\_FANOUT is a stored procedure that provides access to the databases represented by a shard map.",
      "pos": [
        13195,
        13302
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The stored procedure takes the following parameters:",
      "pos": [
        13303,
        13355
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        13362,
        13455
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Server name<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> (nvarchar): Fully qualified name of the logical server hosting the shard map."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        13461,
        13536
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Shard map database name<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> (nvarchar): The name of the shard map database."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        13542,
        13642
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>User name<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> (nvarchar): The user name to log into the shard map database and the remote databases."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        13648,
        13695
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Password<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> (nvarchar): Password for the user."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        13701,
        13783
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Shard map name<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> (nvarchar): The name of the shard map to be used for the query."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        13789,
        13839
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Query<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: The query to be executed on each shard."
    },
    {
      "content": "It uses the shard map information provided in the invocation parameters to execute the given statement on all shards registered with the shard map.",
      "pos": [
        13841,
        13988
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Any results are merged using UNION ALL semantics similar to Multi-Shard Queries.",
      "pos": [
        13989,
        14069
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The result also includes the additional ‘virtual’ column with the remote database name.",
      "pos": [
        14070,
        14157
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that the same credentials are used to connect to the shard map database and to the shards.",
      "pos": [
        14159,
        14254
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        14256,
        14268
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Example<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>:"
    },
    {
      "content": "Connectivity for tools",
      "pos": [
        14422,
        14444
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use familiar SQL DB connection strings to your Elastic Database query database to connect your BI and data integration tools.",
      "pos": [
        14445,
        14578
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Make sure that SQL Server is supported as a data source for your tool.",
      "pos": [
        14579,
        14649
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Then use external objects in the Elastic Database query database just like with any other SQL Server database that you would connect to with your tool.",
      "pos": [
        14650,
        14801
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Best practices",
      "pos": [
        14806,
        14820
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Make sure that the shard map manager database and the databases defined in the shard map allow access from Microsoft Azure in their firewall rules.",
      "pos": [
        14826,
        14973
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is necessary so that the Elastic Database query database can connect to them.",
      "pos": [
        14974,
        15056
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure SQL DB Firewall<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/ee621782.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        15057,
        15163
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "An elastic database query does not validate or enforce the data distribution defined by the external table.",
      "pos": [
        15169,
        15276
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If your actual data distribution is different from the distribution specified in your table definition, your queries may yield unexpected results.",
      "pos": [
        15277,
        15423
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "An elastic database query works best for queries where most of the computation can be done on the shards.",
      "pos": [
        15429,
        15534
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You typically get the best query performance with selective filter predicates that can be evaluated on the shards or joins over the partitioning keys that can be performed in a partition-aligned way on all shards.",
      "pos": [
        15535,
        15748
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Other query patterns may need to load large amounts of data from the shards to the head node and may experience poor performance.",
      "pos": [
        15749,
        15878
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cost",
      "pos": [
        15883,
        15887
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Elastic Database query is included with the cost of Azure SQL Database databases.",
      "pos": [
        15889,
        15974
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that topologies are supported where remote databases are in a different data center than the elastic database query endpoint, but data egress from remote databases is charged at regular Azure egress rates.",
      "pos": [
        15975,
        16185
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Preview limitations",
      "pos": [
        16190,
        16209
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are a few things to keep in mind with the preview:",
      "pos": [
        16211,
        16267
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Elastic Database query feature will initially only be available in the SQL DB v12 Premium performance tier, although remote databases accessed by an elastic database query may be of any tier.",
      "pos": [
        16274,
        16469
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "External tables referenced by your external data source only support read operations over the remote databases.",
      "pos": [
        16472,
        16583
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can, however, point full Transact-SQL functionality at the elastic database query database where the external table definition itself resides.",
      "pos": [
        16584,
        16730
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This can be useful to, for example, to persist temporary results using SELECT column_list INTO local_table, or to define stored procedures on the elastic database query database which refer to external tables.",
      "pos": [
        16731,
        16940
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Parameters in queries currently cannot be pushed to remote databases.",
      "pos": [
        16946,
        17015
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Parameterized queries will need to bring all data to the head node and may suffer from bad performance depending on the data size.",
      "pos": [
        17016,
        17146
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A temporary workaround is to avoid parameters in your queries or to use the RECOMPILE option to have parameters automatically replaced with their current values.",
      "pos": [
        17147,
        17308
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Column-level statistics over external tables are currently not supported.",
      "pos": [
        17311,
        17384
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Elastic Database query currently does not perform shard elimination when predicates over the sharding key would allow to safely exclude certain remote databases from processing.",
      "pos": [
        17387,
        17568
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As a result, queries will always touch all remote databases represented by the external data sources of the query.",
      "pos": [
        17569,
        17683
      ]
